Introduction¶

We will investigate the TMDB movie dataset. This dataset contains information about 10,000 movies in the period from 1960 to 2015 collected from The Movie Database (TMDb),including user ratings,revenue,budget,genres,runtime,popularity. We will ivestigate this dataset to answer some questions:

   1 --> What is the average budget and revenue of movies at this period?
   2 --> What is the highest rating movie and who is its director?
   3 --> Does budget affect revenue over time??
   4 --> Do genres affect revenue?
   5 --> Does runtime affect revenue over time?
   6 --> Does vote affect revenue?

Issues in our Data¶

1st issue¶

There are NaN values (23 in genres) and (44 in derictor)

2nd issue¶

There is one row is duplicated

3th issue¶

There are values in the columns (budget, revenue, runtime) that don't make sense.

Cleaning Data¶

1st issue¶

The number of NaN values in genres and derictor columns is small so we will drop it

In [13]:
df.dropna(inplace=True)

2nd issue¶

We will drop duplicated rows

In [14]:
df.drop_duplicates(inplace=True)

3st issue¶

There are values in the columns (budget, revenue, runtime) that don't make sense,so that we will take the minimum value that make sense and replace all values that is less than it with NaN.

In [17]:
# we will consider the minimum value that make sense in both budget and revenue is 1,000,000$.
#  we will consider the minimum value that make sense in runtime is 1h and the maximum value is 5h.
columns = ['budget', 'revenue', 'runtime']
def fix_columns(df,coulumns):
    for column in columns:
        if column == 'budget' or column == 'revenue':
            df[column].mask(df[column] < 1000000,inplace=True)
        else:
            df[column].mask(df[column] < 60,inplace=True)
            df[column].mask(df[column] > 300,inplace=True)

fix_columns(df,columns)

Research Question 3 (Does budget affect revenue over time?)¶

In [25]:
# we droupby release_year and find the mean of budget and revenue and then plot the relation between them
budget_vs_revenue = df.groupby('release_year')[['budget','revenue']].mean()
budget_vs_revenue.plot(x='budget', y='revenue', kind='scatter',figsize=(8, 8),color='red')
plt.title('The Budget effect on Revenue over time', fontsize=14);

From the figure above we conclude that over time the more the budget the more the revenue.

Conclusions¶

We investigated the TMDB movie dataset and we assessed,cleaned and explored it to answer our questions which are:

1)What is the average budget and revenue of movies at this period?¶

=> The average budget at thie period is 33061223.483132027\ => The average budget at thie period is 99992550.20665742

2)What is the highest rating movie and who is its director in this period?¶

=> The highest rating movie at that period is (The Story of Film: An Odyssey) and its director is (Mark Cousins)

3)Does budget affect revenue over time?¶

=> From the figure above we conclude that over time the more the budget the more the revenue.

4)Do genres affect revenue?¶

=> yes, the genres affect revenue for example: The genre with highest revenue in this periode is (Action|Adventure|Fantasy|Science Fiction) The genres with lowest revenue in this periode are (Drama|Thriller|Crime),(Action|Animation|Science Fiction),(Comedy) and (Thriller|Horror|Comedy).

5)Does runtime affect revenue over time?¶

=> in This periode, the movies with average runtime between 100 to 110 minute have average revenue more than other movies.

6)Does vote affect revenue over time?¶

=> in This periode, the movies with average vote = 6.0 have the highest average revenue

Limitations¶

  • I couldn't find the correlation between the popularity and revenue and i couldn't specify the values that don't makke sense in the popularity column,so we have to konw what is the minimum value of popularity tha mkes sence and how was the popularity values calculated? and to find the crrelation between it and revenue it must be calculated based on ticket sales.
  • I also found NaN values in both genres and directro columns and because the number of NaN values in them is small i removed all rows with NaN values using ```df.dropna()
  • I also found one duplicated row and i removed it using ```df,drop_duplicates()
  • I also found some values that don't makes sense in each of budget,revenue and runtime columns like [0, 1, 2, 16 ] in budget and revenue columns and values like [1, 0, 20, 30, 800, 950] in runtime column so i decided that take the minimum value that make sense in budget and revenue columns is 1,000,000 and the min and max values that make sense in runtime column are 60, 300 respectively and replace the values that are not the specific range with NaN.
